ed-with-gifs-445f06792370?source=post_page-----445f06792370--------------------------------"><p class="bf b bg bh dx"><span class="iv"></span>Aug 17, 2020<span class="iw">·</span>8 min read<svg class="is it iu" width="15" height="15" viewBox="0 0 15 15" aria-label="Member only content"><path d="M7.44 2.32c.03-.1.09-.1.12 0l1.2 3.53a.29.29 0 0 0 .26.2h3.88c.11 0 .13.04.04.1L9.8 8.33a.27.27 0 0 0-.1.29l1.2 3.53c.03.1-.01.13-.1.07l-3.14-2.18a.3.3 0 0 0-.32 0L4.2 12.22c-.1.06-.14.03-.1-.07l1.2-3.53a.27.27 0 0 0-.1-.3L2.06 6.16c-.1-.06-.07-.12.03-.12h3.89a.29.29 0 0 0 .26-.19l1.2-3.52z"></path></svg></p></a></span></div></div><div class="n ix iy iz ja jb jc jd je jf"><div class="n o"><div class="jg s"><div class="ca" aria-hidden="false" aria-describedby="postFooterSocialMenu" aria-labelledby="postFooterSocialMenu"><div><div class="ca" role="tooltip" aria-hidden="false"><button class="el em ce cf cg ch ci cj ck bq en eo cl ep eq" aria-controls="postFooterSocialMenu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Share Post"><svg width="25" height="25" class="r"><g fill-rule="evenodd"><path d="M15.6 5a.42.42 0 0 0 .17-.3.42.42 0 0 0-.12-.33l-2.8-2.79a.5.5 0 0 0-.7 0l-2.8 2.8a.4.4 0 0 0-.1.32c0 .12.07.23.16.3h.02a.45.45 0 0 0 .57-.04l2-2V10c0 .28.23.5.5.5s.5-.22.5-.5V2.93l2.02 2.02c.08.07.18.12.3.13.11.01.21-.02.3-.08v.01"></path><path d="M18 7h-1.5a.5.5 0 0 0 0 1h1.6c.5 0 .9.4.9.9v10.2c0 .5-.4.9-.9.9H6.9a.9.9 0 0 1-.9-.9V8.9c0-.5.4-.9.9-.9h1.6a.5.5 0 0 0 .35-.15A.5.5 0 0 0 9 7.5a.5.5 0 0 0-.15-.35A.5.5 0 0 0 8.5 7H7a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v10c0 1.1.9 2 2 2h11a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V9a2 2 0 0 0-2-2"></path></g></svg></button></div></div></div></div><div class="jh s"><span><a href="https://medium.com/m/signin?actionUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2F_%2Fbookmark%2Fp%2F445f06792370&amp;operation=register&amp;redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fuxdesign.cc%2F19-things-ux-researchers-hate-to-hear-explained-with-gifs-445f06792370&amp;source=post_actions_header--------------------------bookmark_preview-----------" class="el em ce cf cg ch ci cj ck bq en eo cl ep eq" rel="noopener"><svg width="25" height="25" viewBox="0 0 25 25" fill="none" class="ji"><path d="M18 2.5a.5.5 0 0 1 1 0V5h2.5a.5.5 0 0 1 0 1H19v2.5a.5.5 0 1 1-1 0V6h-2.5a.5.5 0 0 1 0-1H18V2.5zM7 7a1 1 0 0 1 1-1h3.5a.5.5 0 0 0 0-1H8a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v14a.5.5 0 0 0 .8.4l5.7-4.4 5.7 4.4a.5.5 0 0 0 .8-.4v-8.5a.5.5 0 0 0-1 0v7.48l-5.2-4a.5.5 0 0 0-.6 0l-5.2 4V7z" fill="#292929"></path></svg></a></span></div><div class="s bd"></div></div></div></div></div></div><p id="11b5" class="jj jk gq jl b hp jm jn hs jo jp jq jr js jt ju jv jw jx jy jz ka gj hn kb"><span class="s kc kd ke ej kf kg kh ki kj at">In</span> the past few years, I’ve been working with a bunch of different clients, with different strategies. However, I have always heard shockingly similar statements!</p><p id="a822" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">If you are working with a UX researcher or wondering what it’s like to be a UX Researcher, then here’s a comprehensive guide to the challenges we face, and the things we are used to hearing all the time.</p><p id="08d3" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">I have also written the sequel to this blog which is <a class="el kp" rel="noopener" href="/31-things-you-shouldnt-say-to-a-ux-designer-explained-with-gifs-46c69e2c0380">“31 things you shouldn’t say to a <strong class="jl gr">UX Designer</strong>”</a>.</p><div class="kq kr ks kt ku kv"><a target="_blank" rel="noopener" href="/31-things-you-shouldnt-say-to-a-ux-designer-explained-with-gifs-46c69e2c0380"><div class="ex n z"><div class="kw n ao p kx ky"><h2 class="bf gr dn bh kz la lb lc ld le lf gp hn">31 things you shouldn’t say to a UX Designer (explained with GIFs)</h2><div class="lg s"><h3 class="bf b dn bh kz la lb lc ld le lf dx">A comprehensive guide with the reasons behind them</h3></div><div class="lh s"><p class="bf b li bh kz la lb lc ld le lf dx">uxdesign.cc</p></div></div><div class="lj s"><div class="lk s ll lm ln lj lo lp kv"></div></div></div></a></div></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="9bd4" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">1. “We don’t need a report”</h1><p id="4f95" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">Well, I am not a<span id="rmm"><span id="rmm"> </span></span>big fan of reports, analyzing user-research results, and creating reports is often the most time-consuming part of a user-research project.</p><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="nf ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">GIF from <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/xUPJPgq5NcxbKHrcXK/html5" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">SpongeBobSquarePants</a> on <a href="https://giphy.com" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure><h2 id="c1f1" class="nl ly gq bf lz nm nn hr mc no np hu mf hv nq hx mj hy nr ia mn ib ns id mr nt hn">Why do we write reports then?</h2><p id="4b92" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">At least one person in the product team should be accountable to document the findings, ensuring that everyone has a shared understanding of the findings and recommendations.</p></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="553d" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">2. “This method is too expensive and time-consuming”</h1><p id="4485" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">Budget and time are the frequently mentioned excuses for not doing any user research. Jakob Nielsen has an advocate of “<a href="https://www.nngroup.com/articles/discount-usability-20-years/" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">discount usability</a>”.</p><p id="58ff" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn"><strong class="jl gr">Reality: </strong>There are quick and dirty techniques for incentives, user recruitment, and tools used that can make UX research quick and affordable. For example, using gift cards as incentives and recruiting through social media.</p><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="nu ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">GIF from <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/3oxHQon5BGolQoUUzC/html5" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">CBC</a> on <a href="https://giphy.com" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="fceb" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">3. “Let’s use one-way mirrors”</h1><p id="3011" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">If you really value high-quality research insights, then you should understand how one-way mirrors work and re-consider using them.</p><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="nv ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">GIF from <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/season-8-the-simpsons-8x14-l2Je9gXDFYPMpOZGw" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">Simpsons</a> on <a href="https://giphy.com" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure><h2 id="828a" class="nl ly gq bf lz nm nn hr mc no np hu mf hv nq hx mj hy nr ia mn ib ns id mr nt hn">What’s not good about it?</h2><p id="61b6" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">I’ve been on both sides of the mirror when using this setup for research. <a href="https://www.keepitusable.com/blog/why-you-should-not-use-one-way-mirrors-for-ux-research/" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">There are many different issues with a one-way mirror</a> and this could be the subject of another article, but here is one of the main reasons:</p><h2 id="64e7" class="nl ly gq bf lz nm nn hr mc no np hu mf hv nq hx mj hy nr ia mn ib ns id mr nt hn">Ironic process theory</h2><p id="82d6" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">When using this setup, due to ethics we must tell the users that they are being observed by people on the other side of the mirror. But consider when someone asks you not to think of a pink elephant, the first thing you think about is a pink elephant. We call this the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ironic_process_theory" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">Ironic Process Theory</a> or the White Bear Principle in Psychology.</p><p id="7108" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">So when we tell users about the setup, their attention is drawn to the fact that they are being observed.Some participants are fine with this and they’ll forget about the mirror but then they mention how they felt like and they were being watched.</p><p id="379e" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn"><em class="nw">Just ask yourself, how would you feel in a room while knowing there are people watching you behind a mirror?</em></p></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="490b" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">4. “Did you ask the user what they like about the product?”</h1><p id="6a03" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">While this question helps researchers start a conversation, it doesn’t tell us <em class="nw">nearly</em> enough. Consider these examples:</p><blockquote class="nx ny nz"><p id="d81b" class="jj jk nw jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn"><strong class="jl gr">Scenario A</strong></p><p id="7e57" class="jj jk nw jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">Q: What do you like about this product?</p><p id="e006" class="jj jk nw jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">A: I actually love the cool animation that I see when I press the buttons in the app.</p></blockquote><h2 id="28f8" class="nl ly gq bf lz nm nn hr mc no np hu mf hv nq hx mj hy nr ia mn ib ns id mr nt hn">What we ask instead:</h2><p id="ee33" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">If we have to ask users what they like, at least we follow up with <em class="nw">why</em> they do. <br/><strong class="jl gr">If we stop here, we might end up thinking to yourself: We’ve got to add more animations to the app!</strong></p><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd fw fx paragraph-image"><div class="fw fx oa"><div class="ne s at of"><div class="og ng s"><div class="fe ob et fh fd oc v kz od oe"><img alt="" class="et fh fd oc v oh oi ae" src="https://miro.medium.com/freeze/max/60/1*3mtz0XJsE1VwlgF3UOZ28A.gif?q=20" width="500" height="281" role="presentation"/></div><img alt="" class="fe ob et fh fd oc v c" width="500" height="281" role="presentation"/><noscript><img alt="" class="et fh fd oc v" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/1000/1*3mtz0XJsE1VwlgF3UOZ28A.gif" width="500" height="281" srcSet="https://miro.medium.com/max/552/1*3mtz0XJsE1VwlgF3UOZ28A.gif 276w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1000/1*3mtz0XJsE1VwlgF3UOZ28A.gif 500w" sizes="500px" role="presentation"/></noscript></div></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">GIF from <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/teamcoco-conan-obrien-kevin-hart-3oz8xMbKLAkRLHYNgI" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">Team Coco</a> on <a href="https://giphy.com" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure><p id="61d3" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">However, when we follow up with a <em class="nw">why </em>question:</p><blockquote class="nx ny nz"><p id="a879" class="jj jk nw jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn"><strong class="jl gr">Scenario B</strong></p><p id="5952" class="jj jk nw jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">Q: Why do you like the animations?</p><p id="4bb5" class="jj jk nw jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">A: Hmm.. I think it’s because it gives me some sort of feedback, like I know for sure that the app’s transmitting the data.</p></blockquote><p id="7971" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">Now it’s clear that it’s really the feedback loop, not the animations per se, that users want.</p></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="ec16" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">5. “Let’s collect some NPS”</h1><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="oj ng s"></div></div></figure><blockquote class="ok"><p id="977b" class="ol om gq bf on oo op oq or os ot ka dx">UX researchers should not use the NPS or, if that’s not an option, ignore it. Jared Spool</p></blockquote><p id="a666" class="jj jk gq jl b hp ou jm jn hs ov jo jp jq ow jr js jt ox ju jv jw oy jx jy ka gj hn">According to MeasuringU: “The concerns about the Net Promoter Score are less because of its inherent measurement flaws, but because it’s misused or used in the wrong context.”</p><blockquote class="nx ny nz"><p id="e903" class="jj jk nw jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">“This is like using a screwdriver to hammer a nail into the wall. That might get the job done, but there’s a better tool for the job. If the job is to uncover usability problems in a mobile app or know what features to add to the software, there are better tools for the job”. — <a href="https://measuringu.com/nps-harmful/" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">MeasuringU</a></p></blockquote><p id="2f95" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">Jared Spool <a href="https://articles.uie.com/net-promoter-score-considered-harmful-and-what-ux-professionals-can-do-about-it/" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">has written a strong critique</a> of the NPS.</p></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="3daa" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">6. “Anybody can read a script and take notes”</h1><p id="6f72" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">Sometimes upper management proposes hiring low-paid employees to moderate usability tests as a way to save money. This tragedy happens because someone might think that “anybody can read a script and take notes”.</p><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="oz ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">GIF from <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/recordingacademy-grammys-the-l0HegPJ7BGBVjuI3S/links" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">Grammys</a> on <a href="https://giphy.com" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure><p id="9a79" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">Obviously, moderating usability tests requires skills and experience in creating the right rapport with research participants, posing the right questions, probing with additional questions, and so on.</p></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="2166" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">7. “I’ll show my design to you when it’s finished”</h1><p id="ca22" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">What do you mean by <em class="nw">finished</em>? Nothing is perfect. And as long as there is room for improvement, nothing is finished.</p><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="pa ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">GIf From <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/hyperrpg-game-funny-1QaYj314HbqFotsWIP" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">Hyper RPG</a> on <a href="https://giphy.com" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure><h2 id="743d" class="nl ly gq bf lz nm nn hr mc no np hu mf hv nq hx mj hy nr ia mn ib ns id mr nt hn">What should this kind of “designers” do:</h2><p id="4af2" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">As a UX Designer, you better get rid of the mindset that you <em class="nw">own</em> the design (or product). You don’t. Your users do, eventually.</p><p id="1519" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">You can be a great designer by opening up your ideas and work to constructive criticism.</p></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="c0dc" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">8. “Let’s use our own employees as participants”</h1><p id="c40d" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn"><strong class="jl gr">Or “Let’s have Steve from finance as a participant. He uses that product.”</strong></p><p id="62b0" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">Your company’s employees don’t represent real users. Even if they have some similarities to actual users, their association with your company and their knowledge of the company’s products can affect their behavior and bias their opinions.</p><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="pb ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">Source <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/uf0EYGcobAity/html5" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure><h2 id="ddb4" class="nl ly gq bf lz nm nn hr mc no np hu mf hv nq hx mj hy nr ia mn ib ns id mr nt hn">What do researchers usually do?</h2><ol class=""><li id="d7e0" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka pc pd pe hn">We recruit participants who are representative of our actual users.</li><li id="2db4" class="jj jk gq jl b hp pf jm jn hs pg jo jp jq ph jr js jt pi ju jv jw pj jx jy ka pc pd pe hn">Resist the temptation to use internal employees as research participants — unless they’re representative of your users, and they don’t have insider knowledge of the product you’re testing.</li></ol></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="f861" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">9. “We can just do a survey”</h1><p id="719e" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">Surveys are great for gathering quantitative data. But that can’t provide the insights you need to improve on your product.</p><blockquote class="ok"><p id="1f82" class="ol om gq bf on oo pk pl pm pn po ka dx">Surveys are the most dangerous research tool — misunderstood and misused. <a href="https://medium.com/mule-design/on-surveys-5a73dda5e9a0" class="el kp" rel="noopener">Erika Hall</a></p></blockquote><p id="9fc8" class="jj jk gq jl b hp ou jm jn hs ov jo jp jq ow jr js jt ox ju jv jw oy jx jy ka gj hn">To start off, multiple-choice survey questions shut off all other possible options; instead of finding the actual problem, you’re basically asking your users to pick from your pool of hypotheses.</p><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="pa ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">GIF from<a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/5htGFvTSehTxWdysds" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow"> Baroness Von Sketch</a> from <a href="https://giphy.com" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure><blockquote class="nx ny nz"><p id="fa8b" class="jj jk nw jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">On the other hand, <strong class="jl gr">if your survey is qualitative</strong>, you’re essentially asking people to write down what they think or feel. As a general rule, people <em class="gq">hate </em>writing. Especially when they know they’re helping you do your job (you’re supposed to be the one who’s doing the writing in an actual user interview!). In the end, you’ll probably get lousy data.</p></blockquote><h2 id="9bf4" class="nl ly gq bf lz nm nn hr mc no np hu mf hv nq hx mj hy nr ia mn ib ns id mr nt hn">What we do instead:</h2><p id="ffa0" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">It’s simple. We go out and talk to real human beings.</p></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="8bdd" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">10. “Let’s have a focus group”</h1><p id="4b8b" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">Place a group of strangers in a room and ask them for their opinions, chances are you’ll get similar answers from all of them. Because that’s the <em class="nw">social </em>thing to do. Humans are troublesome like that.</p><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="nv ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">GIF from <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/season-8-the-simpsons-8x14-l2Je9gXDFYPMpOZGw" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">Simpsons</a> on <a href="https://giphy.com" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure><h2 id="7f62" class="nl ly gq bf lz nm nn hr mc no np hu mf hv nq hx mj hy nr ia mn ib ns id mr nt hn">What we do instead:</h2><p id="8637" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">We ask users questions, one user at a time. That’s how we can go deep and get insights from each of them.</p></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="9f02" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">11. “Did you ask the user whether they buy this product (if it comes out)”</h1><p id="4a3e" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">The most reasonable, social thing to do after being interviewed for over an hour by someone about a product, is to lie and say “<em class="nw">Yes</em>, I might pay for this product/service”.</p><p id="7365" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn"><strong class="jl gr">And even if they really think that they’ll need your product in the near future, humans suck so much at predicting future behavior that they’re probably wrong.</strong></p><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="pp ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">GIF from <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/season-8-the-simpsons-8x14-l2Je9gXDFYPMpOZGw" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">Simpsons</a> on <a href="https://giphy.com" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h2 id="0174" class="nl ly gq bf lz nm nn hr mc no np hu mf hv nq hx mj hy nr ia mn ib ns id mr nt hn">12. “People don’t scroll that much, research results can’t help. Let’s put the CTA somewhere else”</h2><blockquote class="ok"><p id="a3f9" class="ol om gq bf on oo pk pl pm pn po ka dx">“Although people weren’t used to scrolling in the mid-nineties, nowadays it’s absolutely natural to scroll” — <a href="https://uxmyths.com/post/654047943/myth-people-dont-scroll" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">UXMyths</a></p></blockquote><figure class="pq pr ps pt pu nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="pv ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">GIF from <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/3oEjHSe4OCjZGHlgOs/html5" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">Wale</a> on <a href="https://giphy.com" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure><h2 id="b444" class="nl ly gq bf lz nm nn hr mc no np hu mf hv nq hx mj hy nr ia mn ib ns id mr nt hn">You don’t have to squeeze everything into the top of your homepage!</h2></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="927a" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">13. “Read the research protocols to Participants Verbatim”</h1><p id="441b" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">When I was studying Human-Computer Interaction during my master’s degree, I heard a lot of times that one way to avoid biasing the user tests is by reading the research protocol word by word to each participant.</p><p id="77c0" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn"><strong class="jl gr"><em class="nw">“Hi, my name is Hossein Raspberry. I am going to read you all the instructions so each participant receives the same information….”</em></strong></p><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="nf ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">GIF from Games <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/j0Gyhnl3WrB2Uj5ETK/html5" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">Asmodeegames</a> on <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/j0Gyhnl3WrB2Uj5ETK/html5" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure><h2 id="8d46" class="nl ly gq bf lz nm nn hr mc no np hu mf hv nq hx mj hy nr ia mn ib ns id mr nt hn">Why this is not working?</h2><p id="8e56" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">This makes it difficult to establish a good rapport with the participant. Also it makes the user feel unnatural as if they are part of a very formal research.</p></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="fe6e" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">14. “I thought we could all meet together”. User said.</h1><p id="a051" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">Well, this is not necessarily something we hate hearing, and it is not even a user’s fault!</p><p id="ac08" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn"><strong class="jl gr">But</strong> it is funny and surprising when you show up to conduct a contextual inquiry and then you find that the participant has invited several coworkers to participate in what’s suddenly become an impromptu focus group.</p><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="nf ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">GIF from <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/season-8-the-simpsons-8x14-l2Je9gXDFYPMpOZGw" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">Simpsons</a> on <a href="https://giphy.com" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure><h2 id="85f3" class="nl ly gq bf lz nm nn hr mc no np hu mf hv nq hx mj hy nr ia mn ib ns id mr nt hn">Why not?</h2><p id="1a01" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">A group discussion doesn’t let us observe tasks or have individual discussions.</p><blockquote class="nx ny nz"><p id="fc79" class="jj jk nw jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">Howeever, sometimes <a href="https://www.uxmatters.com/mt/archives/2018/09/case-study-adapting-a-software-development-technique-for-usability-testing.php" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">does make sense to include more than one person</a>.</p></blockquote></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="a6b4" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">15. “Let’s just do some usability testing, no need for generative research”</h1><p id="8563" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">Some product teams think there is no need to conduct generative user research because they have done usability tests. When there is a limited research budget, some people feel that it’s best to use it only on usability testing.</p><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="pw ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">Source <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/j4qzs3jWHUSclotPa0/html5" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">GiphyNews</a></figcaption></figure><h2 id="6657" class="nl ly gq bf lz nm nn hr mc no np hu mf hv nq hx mj hy nr ia mn ib ns id mr nt hn">Why this isn’t working?</h2><p id="a53e" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">A usability study is a great method for evaluating the design, but it doesn’t reveal much information about the users, their tasks, the tools and information they use, or their environment.</p></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="57fb" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">16. “ We can’t get anything worthwhile from talking to such a small number of people”</h1><p id="2c75" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">Nielsen Norman suggests that, for usability testing, testing with <a href="https://www.nngroup.com/articles/why-you-only-need-to-test-with-5-users/" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">five users will find up to 85 percent of the issues</a>.</p><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="oz ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">Source <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/movie-my-cousin-vinny-3o7btQDFlvGcv8PXt6" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure><p id="e180" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn"><strong class="jl gr">Qualitative methods and usability testing can reveal important patterns with small sample sizes.</strong></p></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="4c6a" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">17. “It will be sufficient to test it with users at the end of the build”</h1><p id="5397" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">One of the more common forms of UX research is to conduct evaluative testing, which entails testing with users once a product or service has been built.</p><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="pa ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">Source <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/thesimpsons-3orieZkQTAYolfGKyc" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure><p id="d169" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn"><strong class="jl gr">Reality: Frequent usability testing throughout the project will lead to the best results for the business and the users, it’s a win-win!</strong></p></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="a2c3" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">18. “We don’t need a Research Panel”</h1><p id="116c" class="jj jk gq jl b hp mt jm jn hs mu jo jp jq mv jr js jt mw ju jv jw mx jx jy ka gj hn">A research panel allows researchers to do more in a shorter time, with less of the administrative busy-work.</p><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="px ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">Source <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/reaction-bob-office-space-TU0YWTjo2e208" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h1 id="83f5" class="lx ly gq bf lz ma mb jm mc md me jo mf mg mh mi mj mk ml mm mn mo mp mq mr ms hn">19. “We are a startup, we don’t need UX research yet…”</h1><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd"><div class="ne s at"><div class="pa ng s"></div></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">Source <a href="https://giphy.com/gifs/LKTTAzGboJGzC/html5" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">giphy</a></figcaption></figure><p id="0d7f" class="jj jk gq jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn">Just google “ROI of UX Research”. You will find out, the earlier you start to research, the better it is for your business.</p></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><h2 id="6133" class="nl ly gq bf lz nm nn hr mc no np hu mf hv nq hx mj hy nr ia mn ib ns id mr nt hn">UX and Humor</h2><blockquote class="nx ny nz"><p id="c84c" class="jj jk nw jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn"><a class="el kp" rel="noopener" href="/31-things-you-shouldnt-say-to-a-ux-designer-explained-with-gifs-46c69e2c0380"><strong class="jl gr">31 Things you shouldn’t say to a UX Designer (explained with GIFs)</strong></a><strong class="jl gr">.</strong></p><p id="ef0a" class="jj jk nw jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn"><a class="el kp" rel="noopener" href="/13-signs-you-are-dating-a-ux-researcher-329fefa7156e"><strong class="jl gr">13 signs you are dating a UX Researcher</strong></a></p></blockquote><h2 id="97d7" class="nl ly gq bf lz nm nn hr mc no np hu mf hv nq hx mj hy nr ia mn ib ns id mr nt hn">UX and Science</h2><blockquote class="nx ny nz"><p id="4681" class="jj jk nw jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn"><strong class="jl gr"><em class="gq">The s</em></strong><a class="el kp" rel="noopener" href="/the-13-scientific-principles-every-uxer-needs-to-know-b7c347d74351"><strong class="jl gr"><em class="gq">cientific principles every UXer needs to know</em></strong></a></p><p id="bbf4" class="jj jk nw jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn"><a class="el kp" rel="noopener" href="/the-usability-issue-that-caused-1-death-and-38-injuries-97911dfa5c7f"><strong class="jl gr"><em class="gq">The Usability Issue that causesd 1 death and 38 injuries</em></strong></a></p></blockquote><h2 id="1a6a" class="nl ly gq bf lz nm nn hr mc no np hu mf hv nq hx mj hy nr ia mn ib ns id mr nt hn">UX knowledge</h2><blockquote class="nx ny nz"><p id="ae76" class="jj jk nw jl b hp kk jm jn hs kl jo jp jq km jr js jt kn ju jv jw ko jx jy ka gj hn"><a class="el kp" rel="noopener" href="/41-design-terms-you-need-to-know-as-a-ux-researcher-writer-38987ff1d711"><strong class="jl gr"><em class="gq">41 design terms you need to know as a UX Researcher/Writer</em></strong></a></p></blockquote></div></div></section><div class="n p db lq lr ls" role="separator"><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv lw"></span><span class="lt iq ca lu lv"></span></div><section class="gj gk gl du gm"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay gn ba v"><figure class="my mz na nb nc nd fw fx paragraph-image"><div class="fw fx py"><img alt="" class="v lp pz" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/188/0*FTzuM4SC8y5taSzn" width="94" height="40" role="presentation"/></div><figcaption class="nh ni fy fw fx nj nk bf b bg bh dx">The UX Collective donates US$1 for each article published in our platform. This story contributed to <a href="https://www.bayareablackdesigners.com/" class="el kp" rel="noopener nofollow">Bay Area Black Designers</a>: a professional development community for Black people who are digital designers and researchers in the San Francisco Bay Area. By joining together in community, members share inspiration, connection, peer mentorship, professional development, resources, feedback, support, and resilience. Silence against systemic racism is not an option. Build the design community you believe in.</figcaption></figure></div></div></section></div></article><div class="fe gi ff qg v qh fh qe qi" data-test-id="post-sidebar"><div class="n p"><div class="au av aw ax ay az ba v"><div class="qj n ao"><div class="gi"><div><div class="qk s"><div class="ql s"><a href="https://medium.com/@hosseinraspberry?source=post_sidebar--------------------------post_sidebar-----------" class="el em ce cf cg ch ci cj ck bq en eo cl ep eq" rel="noopener"><h2 class="bf lz dn bh gp hn gj">Hossein Raspberry</h2></a></div><div class="qm s"><p class="bf b bg bh dx">Researcher | Storyteller | Foodie | I love people and words 🇭🇺🇺🇸🇮🇷— On Medium since August 2020</p></div><div class="qn n"><span><a href="https://medium.com/m/signin?actionUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2F_%2Fsubscribe%2Fuser%2Fcb02c9378c36%2F445f06792370&amp;operation=register&amp;redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fuxdesign.cc%2F19-things-ux-researchers-hate-to-hear-explained-with-gifs-445f06792370&amp;user=Hossein%20Raspberry&amp;userId=cb02c9378c36&amp;source=post_sidebar-cb02c9378c36-------------------------follow_sidebar-----------" class="bf b bg bh eb bj ec ed ee ef eg bq br bs eh ei bw bx by bz ca cb" rel="noopener">Follow</a></span></div></div><div class="qo qp v n o bc qq"><div class="lw n"><div class="n o bc"><div class="s at qr qs qt qu qv"><span><a href="https://medium.com/m/signin?act